data.content:
Good news: **this code doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, so it won't throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8. However, the manual `Thread` management pattern has no cancellation support — if a caller *were* to try `Thread.Abort` to cancel work, it would fail on .NET 8.

The recommended migration is to use `Task` + `CancellationToken` for cooperative cancellation:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items, CancellationToken ct = default)
    {
        var tasks = items.Select(item => Task.Run(() => Process(item, ct), ct));
        await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item, CancellationToken ct)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        // simulate work
        Task.Delay(100, ct).Wait(ct);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- **`Thread` → `Task.Run`** — uses the thread pool instead of spawning raw threads
- **`CancellationToken`** — replaces `Thread.Abort` with cooperative cancellation
- **`Task.Delay`** — replaces `Thread.Sleep` (cancellation-aware)
- **`async/await`** — lets callers cancel via `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`

If any upstream code was calling `Thread.Abort` on these threads, replace it with:
```csharp
var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
cts.Cancel(); // instead of thread.Abort()
```
